ers since settings like logLevel and profilingLevel don't replicate across the replica set. When I trigger the rolling restart via StatefulSet patch, the pods will restart in reverse ordinal order (2, 1, 0) due to the OrderedReady policy, and each will pick up the new configuration from the updated configmap. Now I'm ready to write out the implementation steps. Writing kubectl commands... Writing YAML patch... The keyFile path `/keyfile/keyfile` is correct since the initContainer sets it up and mongod will find it when reading the config. Now I need to write out the commands for applying these changes, being careful about which operations can run on secondaries—`setProfilingLevel` works on all members, so each replica can manage its own profiling independently.\n\nFrom the earlier profiling status check, I saw profiling was off but the slow operation threshold was 200ms. I can use `db.setProfilingLevel(0, {slowms: 400})` to adjust the slow query log threshold to 400ms without enabling the profiler itself. One more thing to verify: when I patch the StatefulSet to use the config file with `net.bindIpAll: true`, I need to make sure that doesn't conflict with the current setup. The keyFile path matches what's in the current command, so authentication should work the same way. Now I'm planning the execution steps: update the ConfigMap, apply dynamic changes to all three replica members, patch the StatefulSet to trigger a rolling restart, wait for it to complete, and verify everything works. I need to be careful about which database to run profiling commands on since they might need to be executed on the admin database. I'm settling on using `db.adminCommand()` with `setParameter` to configure both the log level and the slow operation threshold globally, then I'll write out the complete commands.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1758,"cache_read_input_tokens":56329,"cache_